# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beach-handball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:beach-handball/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] The **2014 Beach Handball World Championships** were a twelve-team tournament in both men's and women's beach handball, held at Recife, Brazil from 22–27 July, 2014.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] Just like two years prior, Brazil again won the gold medal in both, the men's and women's competition.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] The twelve teams were split into two groups of six teams.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] After playing a round-robin, the three top ranked team advanced to the Main Round.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] Every team kept the points from preliminary round matches against teams who also advanced.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] In the main round every team had 3 games against the opponents they did not face in the preliminary round.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] The top four teams advanced to the Semifinals.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] The three bottom ranked team from each preliminary round group were packed into one group.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] The points won against the teams who were also in this group were valid.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] Every team played three games and after those round there wereplacement matches from 7th–12th place.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] Matches were played in sets, the team that wins two sets is the winner of a match.
[src:beach-handball/2014-beach-handball-world-championships] When teams are equal in points the head-to-head result was decisive.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:beach-handball/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatic gymnasts perform in one of five units: pairs (same-gender or mixed) or same-gender groups (three for women, four for men).
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In each partnership, the gymnasts' different sizes and abilities will be balanced to complement each other in order to carry out the complex moves.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Some will mainly carry out supporting and pitching roles and are known as bases.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] They are then balanced with usually smaller gymnasts who become the 'tops'.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In men's and women's groups there are also one or two 'middles', who are like another base who usually will support the top while balancing on the base.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In competition, partnerships perform a routine to music, which has usually been choreographed specifically for them.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The gymnasts carry out their acrobatic moves and combine them with dance, all in time to and in keeping with the style of the music.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Partnerships are judged on artistry/dance, execution of skills, and difficulty of skills, with the scoring emphasis on execution.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The rules for the sport, known as the Code of Points, are governed by the FIG.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] These rules are subject to change every four years in line with the Olympic cycle, as in other disciplines of gymnastics.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Acrobatics have a long history dating back thousands of years across the world and appeared in festivals, early circuses, and later vaudeville acts as a form of entertainment.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first use of acrobatics as a specific sport was in the Soviet Union in the 1930s, though its development was interrupted by the World War II.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The first competition, for men only, was held in 1939, with a women's event being added the next year.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1957, the first international competition was held between the Soviet Union, Poland, Bulgaria, and East Germany.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The International Federation of Sports Acrobatics was established in 1973, and the first world championships were held in 1974.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The federation dissolved in 1998, and acrobatic gymnastics was from then on governed by the FIG.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] It was originally called **sports acrobatics** but has been known as **acrobatic gymnastics** since 2007.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In addition to the current five categories, two additional categories for tumbling (men's and women's) were included until the 1999 World Championships, though some groups still involve tumbling events.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In the United States, the first national sports acrobatics organization was called the United States Sports Acrobatics Federation (USSAF).
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Founded in 1975, its name was changed to the United States Sports Acrobatics (USSA) in the 1990s.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The USSA then merged with USA Gymnastics in 2002, and acrobatic gymnastics is now a discipline therein.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] For example, the 28th Acrobatic Gymnastics European Championships were held in Rzeszów, Poland, in October 2017.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] There are also numerous national, state, and regional competitions that are held in each country.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Local and regional competitions often form the qualification stages required to compete at national championships.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] There is no requirement from the FIG for gymnasts to have qualified through their own national championships to compete internationally, but local governing bodies will often make their national team selections based on performance at national competition.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the London 2012 Olympics, acrobatic partnerships were seen performing before the Olympic gymnastics' events, and during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gold, silver, and bronze medals are generally awarded in the usual fashion, although in some competitions, a minimum score is required to qualify for medals.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts may only participate in one level and unit (pair or group) at a competition.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The number of required routines at a competition depends on the level at which the gymnasts are competing.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] At the junior and senior levels, all three routines mentioned below are required.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] At lower age levels, only a single simpler routine is required.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Each of the routine types has a different emphasis, but all include tumbling and dance as elements.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic (formerly known as Tempo) – These routines demonstrate power, strength and grace through the performance of acrobatic moves that involve the phases of spring, flight, rotation, and landing.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] This often involves the base, or bases in the partnership propelling the top through the air and through a series of somersaults or twists.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The top is generally caught or supported in the landing by their base(s).
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Dynamic routines last approximately two minutes.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Combined – At the more senior levels of competition (11–19 through senior levels), a third routine must be performed that combines both balance and dynamic moves, along with the usual tumbling and dance (tumbling is not required from senior level athletes).
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Typically, it is performed as a final's routine, with a duration, depending upon the level of competition, of approximately 2 minutes and 30 seconds.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in artistic gymnastics, compulsory routines, consisting of a prescribed sequence of elements, were previously required along with optional routines, consisting of elements chosen by the gymnasts and their coaches, although this is no longer the case at the highest level of the sport.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The final score of a routine is the sum of the **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry** scores, minus any additional penalties incurred.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] For seniors, the difficulty score is open-ended with no maximum, while the execution and artistry scores have a starting value of 10 points and are lowered for specific mistakes made by the gymnasts.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Emphasis is put on the execution score, which is doubled to provide the final score.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Difficulty is the sum of the difficulty value assigned to each element the gymnasts perform during an exercise.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Senior gymnasts have no difficulty limit.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts submit a 'tariff sheet' listing their planned elements ahead of the competition.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution is the degree to which the gymnasts performs an element with aesthetic and technical perfection.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Execution penalties are subtracted from the starting score of 10 and concern aspects such as the amplitude of flight elements, correctness of body shapes, and controlled landings.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties range from 0.1 for small mistakes, such as a small bend at the waist in a handstand, to 0.5 for large ones.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] A top falling rather than being caught by a partner is a one-point deduction.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Artistry evaluates the relationship of the gymnasts with each other and the music, the choreography of the routine, and the variety displayed in a routine.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The choreography of the routine use the whole floor and flow logically from one element to the next, gymnasts should display emotion throughout the performance and perform well with each other, and the choreography should show creativity and original elements.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Penalties are deducted from the final score.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] In 1978, each element was evaluated as either a Group 1 element or Group 2 element, with Group 1 elements being worth 0.4 difficulty points and Group 2 elements being worth 0.2.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] A routine required at least five elements, at least three of which were required to be Group 2 elements.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The minimum difficulty level started a routine at 9.0 points, with the maximum being 10.0.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] For the 2025–2028 code, changes were made to encourage variety and allow for mixed series of balance and dynamic elements while keeping the code relatively stable for the benefit of countries where acrobatic gymnastics is still developing.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] The judging panels of acrobatic gymnastics are similar to other disciplines of gymnastics where different panels of judges are overseen by a head judge, and each panel has a 'Chair of the Judging Panel' (CJP) who oversees that panel's activities.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasts train new elements with plenty of safety mats as well as safety harnesses, which are also called spotting belts.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Gymnasiums must have a high ceiling to make sure gymnasts at the top of pyramids or being thrown high in the air do not hit the ceiling.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] To support a grip on the head, bases will often keep their hair short or shave the area gripped by a top, and they may use chalk to assist the top's grip.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Most acrobatic gymnastics injuries occur in the lower limbs, such as to the knee and ankle, with wrist injuries also being relatively frequent.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Ligament injuries are common, though one study found a sex difference, with female gymnasts most frequently having ligament injuries while male gymnasts were most likely to have tendon injuries.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] Bases are more frequently injured than tops, and tops are more prone to acute injuries such as fractures or sprains, while bases are more prone to overuse injuries.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines, disordered eating is a concern, although it is not well-studied in acrobatic gymnastics in particular.
[src:beach-handball/acrobatic-gymnastics] One study surveyed female gymnasts aged 10–19 participating in a World Cup event for indicators of disordered eating; they found that older gymnasts, gymnasts acting as bases, and gymnasts from Eastern Europe were at higher risk of disordered eating behaviors.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The performance area is a floor 10 metres (33 ft) square.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Trio, groups, and aerobic dance and step groups may consist of gymnasts of any combination of genders.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts frequently compete in more than one competition category at the same competition and are allowed to compete in up to three at the World Championships.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] All routines last for 1 minute and 20 to 30 seconds.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Women must wear a leotard with tights or a full-length unitard, and men must wear either a form-fitting top with shorts or pants or a full-length unitard.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Men are not permitted to have sequins or long sleeves on their competition costume.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] For individual, pairs, trio, and group routines, scores have three components: **difficulty**, **execution**, and **artistry**, which are added together to create the final score.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] For dance and step routines, scores only consist of artistry and execution scores.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual routines consist of eight elements; performing more elements incurs a deduction.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Elements include dynamic strength elements such as pushup variations and leg circles, static strength elements like planches that may be performed while turning on the hands, jumps, turns, and splits.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Limited acrobatic elements such as handsprings are allowed as well.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Up to three elements may be performed in combination with each other for a connection bonus.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Gymnasts must perform a variety of elements during their routines.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Individual men must perform a dynamic leap element and may not perform flexibility or balance elements, while individual women must perform a turn.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Pairs, trios, and groups must perform the same elements simultaneously and show multiple instances of two or more people working together in a collaborative movement.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The **difficulty score** is calculated by adding together the difficulty values of the performed elements, then dividing by a different divisor depending on the competition category, and for trios and groups, gender makeup.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] For example, the difficulty a group routine performed by five men will be divided by 2, that of a mixed-gender group by 1.9, and that of an all-women group by 1.8.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The **execution score** begins at 10 points, and deductions are taken for wrong technique or mistakes.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] For pairs, trios, and groups, the worst performance of an element across all gymnasts is used to take deductions.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The **artistry score** has a maximum of 10 points.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Routines are evaluated a variety of criteria, such as creativity, musicality and music composition, quality of aerobic movement patterns, use of space, and performance quality.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Aerobic gymnastics stems from the aerobics trend of the 1980s, which spawned competitions.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The first national aerobic championships were held in the United States in 1984, organized by Howard and Karen Schwartz, who took aerobics from a fitness activity and developed it into a competitive discipline.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] They also organized the first (pre-FIG) World championships in 1990, with 16 participating countries, and the first World Youth Aerobic Championship in 1998, with specific divisions for athletes aged between 8 and 17 years.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1993, various national federations approached the FIG to request it be included as a gymnastics discipline.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] A Code of Points was developed; the first edition was only 20 pages.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1995, the FIG recognised sport aerobics as a new competitive gymnastics discipline, organised judges and coaches courses and launched the first Aerobic Gymnastics World Championships in Paris, with 34 countries sending competitors.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] In 1997, the IWGA (International World Games Association) included Aerobic Gymnastics in the 5th World Games (Lahti, Finland).
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Since 1999, the European Union of Gymnastics has been conducting Aerobic European Gymnastics Championships in every odd year.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] By 2015, 75 national federations participated in aerobic gymnastics.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] As in other gymnastics disciplines such as rhythmic gymnastics, athletes may feel pressured to be thin, especially for athletes with a higher body mass index, even if they are quite thin by typical standards.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] Pressure to lose weight can come from parents, coaches, peers, and other gymnastics authority figures such as judges, and it can lead to disordered eating behaviors.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] A study of athletes competing at the 2022 World Championships found that those who participated in the study trained an average of 16 to 18 hours a week.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] 73% of participants reported an injury occurring in the previous year.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The most common injuries were muscle strains, tears, and ruptures as well as sprains.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] The legs, especially the ankle, knee, and foot, were the most commonly injured areas, followed by the shoulders, wrists, and hands in the upper body, followed by the hip and spine.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] More than half of the participants also reported significant stress.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] In the American sketch comedy television series Key & Peele, the duo parodies the '80s video footage of the National Aerobic Championship in a sketch showing one of the aerobic dancers experiencing a meltdown while dancing to the championship theme song.
[src:beach-handball/aerobic-gymnastics] In the Mannrobics taunt in the video game Team Fortress 2, the Alternate-Fire action resembles some moves done in the 1988 Crystal Light National Aerobic Championship.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:beach-handball/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:beach-handball/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] The **African Beach Games** is a continental multi-sport event held among athletes from Africa.
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] The Games are organised under the governance of the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA).
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] The Games were announced by the ANOCA President, Lassana Palenfo, in May 2015.
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] All of the competing nations are for the African continent.
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] The first Games were held on the island of Sal, Cape Verde in June 2019.
[src:beach-handball/african-beach-games] In October 2021, Baseball5 was added as a full medal sport for the 2023 edition.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] First played in 1990s in Italy, and the 1998 Pan American Beach Handball Championship was first international games.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] The first European Championships was played in the year 2000.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] As of September 2014, Brazil is ranked the number 1 country in the world, and is the winner of the world championship in both men's and women's divisions at the 2014 Beach Handball World Championships.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Matches are played as two 10-minute sets, with a half-time of 5 minutes.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] If teams are tied at the end of a regular set then the teams play for a golden goal.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] If the teams are tied at the end of 2 sets then the teams will participate in a tiebreaker.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] The tie break involves a goalie throwing the ball to their own player while that player attempts to score one-on-one with the opposing goalie.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] During regular play, if the goalkeeper scores a goal this counts as two points, compared to a normal goal scored by an outfield player which counts as 1 point.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Creative or spectacular goals, such as 360-degree jumps and alley-oops, are awarded with two points, as well as in-flights and 6-meter throws.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] In 2021, the Norway women's national beach handball team was fined €1500 for being improperly dressed after the women wore bike shorts instead of bikini bottoms at a European championship match in Bulgaria.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Critics derided the fine and the underlying rule.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Although the Norwegian Handball Federation announced they would pay the fines, pop singer Pink offered to pay for them.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Later, in November 2021, the International Handball Federation changed their dress rules to allow female players to wear some kinds of shorts, specifying "Female athletes must wear short tight pants with a close fit".
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Handball in general has a high incidence of injury, with the most common injuries occurring in the lower body (thighs, knees, ankles), and the upper limbs(bicep, shoulders, elbows).
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] There are several risks specific to beach handball that contribute to injury.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Violent contact is the primary mechanism of severe injury.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] This accounts for 71.4% of reported cases in one study.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Playing position also is a factor, with central defenders and goalkeepers often showing the highest injury incidence.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Age, is in many other sports, is also a contributing factor to injury and accounts for significantly higher overall injury incidence.
[src:beach-handball/beach-handball] Participation in beach handball during the off-season for indoor handball is shown to have lower injury incidence during the indoor season.
